1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,520
 So now we're in the second half of our data modeling exploration.

2
00:00:04,520 --> 00:00:06,120
 We've talked about one to many and

3
00:00:06,120 --> 00:00:08,720
 now we're going to talk about many to many.

4
00:00:08,720 --> 00:00:14,960
 Just to remember, we are in the bowels of a django application and

5
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:21,320
 we're really very much talking about the model.py file and how we mess with that.

6
00:00:21,320 --> 00:00:23,280
 We're talking a little bit about the shell and

7
00:00:23,280 --> 00:00:28,080
 how we can sort of look at the model.py and store stuff in the database.

8
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:34,340
 How we can like migrate, make migrations and update the database and

9
00:00:34,340 --> 00:00:37,000
 then read and write data from the database through the models.

10
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,480
 And so, this, we're sort of narrowing in eventually.

11
00:00:40,480 --> 00:00:44,200
 We're gonna see all the rest of the django application, the views,

12
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:46,320
 the forms, the templates.

13
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:49,000
 And we've done a little bit with routing and a little bit with admin.

14
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,040
 But just remember that we're gonna look at each of these pieces in turn and

15
00:00:53,040 --> 00:00:55,760
 eventually make some sense out of them.

16
00:00:55,760 --> 00:01:01,080
 So, in this data model, which I think is a really cool data model because

17
00:01:01,080 --> 00:01:07,320
 it shows two one to many relationships and two many to many relationships.

18
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:10,200
 One very simple and one a little bit more complex.

19
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:14,680
 Both the genre and the author are example of one to many.

20
00:01:14,680 --> 00:01:18,440
 And just sort of foreshadowing, see the one dot dot asterisk there?

21
00:01:18,440 --> 00:01:23,320
 On both ends of the links, well that basically says one or more.

22
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:27,200
 Up to an infinite, the other one's zero dot dot, the line's kind of covering it.

23
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,400
 Zero or more and one or more.

24
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:35,000
 So the one to many has one on one side, sometimes it has zero or one.

25
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:39,400
 But one on one side and then zero dot dot star or one dot dot star.

26
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:42,120
 So many to many is a different kind of creature.

27
00:01:42,120 --> 00:01:48,960
 So remember how in the last modeling exercise, I kinda, you'll notice,

28
00:01:48,960 --> 00:01:52,840
 I showed you genre and author and then I kinda stopped talking about them.

29
00:01:52,840 --> 00:01:55,000
 I only talked about language and book instance.

30
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:59,040
 So in this one, we're gonna talk about genre and author.

31
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:03,520
 And that's because genre and author are kinda problematic.

32
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:07,800
 Cuz really, each book can have multiple authors.

33
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:10,960
 And each book can be multiple genres.

34
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:14,680
 And so, in that previous lecture, I kept these really simple.

35
00:02:14,680 --> 00:02:18,680
 And you see this syntax here where I'm just kinda making a spreadsheet.

36
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:23,600
 Or another way to be thinking about it would be a single, single wide table with

37
00:02:23,600 --> 00:02:27,080
 all my data in one table, but I'm starting to put commas in.

38
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:29,760
 And so when you have commas in a user interface,

39
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:33,760
 you think of this as perhaps a multi-select, where you have a list of things and

40
00:02:33,760 --> 00:02:36,440
 you can highlight more than one of those things.

41
00:02:36,440 --> 00:02:41,920
 And so anytime you sort of see this pattern, it's another form of replication.

42
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:46,800
 And that is that the Raspberry Pi book can be of the tech genre and

43
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:51,120
 the kids genre, and the wizard stay up late book can be of the tech genre and

44
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:52,840
 the thinking genre, right?

45
00:02:52,840 --> 00:02:56,400
 Some books have one genre, some books have two genres,

46
00:02:56,400 --> 00:02:58,900
 some books have one author, some have two.

47
00:02:58,900 --> 00:03:03,440
 But then the problem is they might have ten authors or 20 authors.

48
00:03:03,440 --> 00:03:06,320
 And so how do we represent these things?

49
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:13,020
 And if you're sort of looking at either a UI or sort of a UI or

50
00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:17,120
 just kind of a flat data table, you start seeing these commas.

51
00:03:17,120 --> 00:03:19,600
 And as soon as you see the commas, you think to yourself,

52
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:24,680
 that is an indicator that this might be a many-to-many relationship.

53
00:03:24,680 --> 00:03:30,480
 So if this were a one-to-many, not one-to-one, this was a one-to-many.

54
00:03:30,480 --> 00:03:34,040
 This was a one-to-many relationship, sort of like what we did with languages.

55
00:03:34,040 --> 00:03:38,800
 We would have a book and that would have a genre foreign key in it that would point

56
00:03:38,800 --> 00:03:43,040
 to a row and a genre table, and that would make some sense, right?

57
00:03:43,040 --> 00:03:47,760
 But that doesn't make sense because we have to have genres more than one.

58
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:49,280
 You could basically decide for

59
00:03:49,280 --> 00:03:52,360
 your application developers that you can't have more than one genre.

60
00:03:52,360 --> 00:03:55,320
 But the application developers would say, sorry, we're librarians.

61
00:03:55,320 --> 00:03:57,800
 And we know that there's more than one genre.

62
00:03:57,800 --> 00:03:59,000
 So you, the programmer,

63
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,760
 have got to come up with a data model that represents that.

64
00:04:02,760 --> 00:04:07,600
 And so if this was a one-to-many, you could have like a genre ID and

65
00:04:07,600 --> 00:04:10,880
 each book would be able to pick a row out of the genre, and

66
00:04:10,880 --> 00:04:13,760
 so they would sort of mark themselves.

67
00:04:13,760 --> 00:04:19,480
 Now, this is another moment where it's a warning sign.

68
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:24,360
 And you're like, well, maybe we would just have two foreign keys.

69
00:04:24,360 --> 00:04:28,760
 And we just, how about books are only allowed to have two genres, you know?

70
00:04:28,760 --> 00:04:30,960
 Maybe one's not enough, but two's enough.

71
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:33,040
 Oh, man, let's make it three.

72
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:38,520
 And so, and people who are doing data modeling earlier, early in their career,

73
00:04:38,520 --> 00:04:42,880
 they were like, yeah, I'll just make a genre ID01, genre ID02, and

74
00:04:42,880 --> 00:04:46,320
 then later like genre ID03, and away you go.

75
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:49,680
 And this is completely wrong.

76
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:52,280
 Because genres, of course, is a weird example.

77
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:57,760
 But if it's authors, there are plenty of books with 8 or 9, 10, 11 authors, right?

78
00:04:57,760 --> 00:05:01,080
 And so this, when you see yourself thinking this in your head,

79
00:05:01,080 --> 00:05:05,840
 it's like, I'll just add like an array of things here.

80
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:09,120
 No, and it has to do with it.

81
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:14,320
 It violates the basic notion of relations and connections, and

82
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:18,800
 how you model stuff to the extent that you can with connections.

83
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:23,200
 And so that leads us to what's called the many to many.

84
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:33,200
 [MUSIC]

